article.headline: Western Kentucky 70, Georgia 67
article.story: ATHENS, Ga. (AP) -- Courtney Lee scored 24 points and Western Kentucky closed the game with a 15-2 run to stun Georgia 70-67 Tuesday night. The Bulldogs (1-1) led 65-55 on Rashaad Singleton's layup with 6:02 remaining but managed just one more basket the rest of the way. Western Kentucky (2-0) took its first lead of the night, 68-67, when Benson Callier made one of two free throws with 19.7 seconds left. Georgia's Mike Mercer missed a shot while slicing into the lane, Lee got the rebound and was fouled. He made two free throws with 6.2 seconds to go. The Bulldogs had one more chance, but Billy Humphrey's 3-pointer bounced off the front of the rim as the buzzer sounded. Georgia was held scoreless over the final 3:45 after Steve Newman's hook shot made it 67-61. Levi Stukes led Georgia with 13 points and became the 36th player in school history to reach 1,000 career points. Georgia led nearly the entire game, but Western Kentucky hung around. The biggest margin of the first half was 25-16 when Mercer scored on a spectacular alley-oop dunk. But the Hilltoppers responded with a 3-pointer by Butch Jointer and a layup by A.J. Slaughter. Georgia led 43-36 at halftime, finishing off with Humphrey's 3-pointer at the buzzer. After Singleton's basket gave Georgia a 10-point lead, matching its biggest of the game, Jeremy Evans converted a three-point play that started Western Kentucky's comeback. The Bulldogs made it easier for the Hilltoppers, throwing the ball away on three straight possessions inside of the 2-minute mark. Georgia coach Dennis Felton dropped to 1-2 against his former team. He coached at Western Kentucky from 1998-2003. This was the third of four games that Georgia was required to play against the Hilltoppers under its buyout of Felton's contract. The road team has won every game so far. The Hilltoppers swept their season-opening swing through Georgia, breezing past Kennesaw State 96-55 on Saturday night. This is the first time they have opened the season with two road wins since 1953. Daniel Emerson added 14 points for Western Kentucky, and Tyrone Brazelton scored 12. Mercer and Humphrey scored 12 apiece for Georgia, while Sundiata Gaines had 10.
